# Payloadify ships as a static, client-side Next.js export (`output: "export"`) with a
# Cloudflare Worker (worker/src/) handling the two things a browser can't do itself: fetching
# arbitrary response headers and DNS lookups. The Worker needs zero secrets/env vars — Cloudflare's
# own DoH endpoint (cloudflare-dns.com) requires no auth, and outbound header fetches need no API
# key. Worker-side config, if ever needed, belongs in wrangler.jsonc's `vars` or `wrangler secret
# put`, entirely separate from this file (which only affects the static Next.js build).
#
# The one `process.env` usage in the whole codebase is `lib/net/apiClient.ts`, which reads
# `NODE_ENV` (always set by Next.js, no `.env` entry needed) to decide whether to call the
# same-origin `/api/...` path (production) or a local `wrangler dev` port (development).
#
# No real variables are needed today — this file remains a placeholder for the future.
